We see that $(\sqrt{100})^2 = 100$, so $\sqrt{100}$ has a value of 10. Since we need to have a value greater than or equal to 10.5, we square this number as well to get an idea of what our starting point for $n$ should be.  $$ (10.5)^2 = (10 + 0.5)^2 = 10^2 + 2(10)(0.5) + 0.5^2 = 100 + 10 + 0.25 = 110.25.$$ So, if $n=111$, then $110.25< n \leq 144$. Therefore, it follows that $$10.5 < \sqrt{n} \leq 12,$$ and the smallest possible value of $n$ is $\boxed{111}$. If you are not convinced by this algebraic approach, consider drawing a coordinate system with both axes ranging from 10 to 12. The line connecting these points will represent all pairs of values whose product is 100. Any point above this line will correspond to a pair of numbers whose product is larger than 100, which means at least one of them must be bigger than 10.5.

