There are three possible outcomes where the two numbers roll to $9$: $(6,3), (5,4),$ or $(4,5)$. Since there are $36$ total possibilities when rolling a die twice, our desired probability is $\dfrac{3}{36} = \boxed{\dfrac{1}{12}}$. We can also use complementary counting here by considering the ways in which we do not get a sum of nine. If we have a sum less than $9$, then one number must be greater than five since if both numbers are at most five then their sum would be less than ten. So for each way of choosing the first number from $6$ to $6$, there are only four ways to choose the second number so that it doesn't make the sum equal to $9$. That gives us $4$ possibilities without getting a sum of $9$. Similarly, if we have a sum greater than $9$, then one number must be greater than four. This leaves us with five choices for either the first or the second number, leading to another $10$ possibilities. Together, this gives us $14$ possibilities that don't give us a sum of nine, leaving us with $22$ possibilities that do give us a sum of nine. Thus the probability is $$\dfrac{22}{36}=\boxed{\dfrac{1}{12}}.$$ Either method works equally well; sometimes one is easier than the other depending on how you think about problems like these. In general, you should feel free to try any method that makes sense to you! For example, you could also solve this problem using algebra by letting the first roll be $x$ and the second roll be $y$. Then we're looking for values of $x$ and $y$ such that $x+y=9$, and since $1\leq x,y\leq 6$, the only possible pairs are $(3,6),(4,5),(5,4),$ and $(6,3)$, giving us the same result as before. The key thing is to remember that whenever you see a word problem, especially one involving probability, always try to translate it into mathematical terms because those often turn out to be much more manageable. After all, no matter how cleverly worded, words are just another way of expressing mathematics!

