We have that $\log_{10} x=-2$. In exponential form, this means that $10^{-2}=x$, or $\boxed{\frac{1}{100}}=x$. Note that we can also use the logarithm power rule to solve for $x$: \begin{align*}
\log_{10} x&=-2\\
\Rightarrow \quad 10^{\log_{10} x}&=10^{-2}\\
\Rightarrow \quad x&=\boxed{\frac{1}{100}}
\end{align*}In general, if $\log_b x=a$, then $b^a=x$. This property is very useful in solving many problems involving logarithms. For example, it would be much harder to solve the problem above without using this property. Therefore, whenever you see an equation like $\log_b y=c$, try converting it into its equivalent exponential form by raising $b$ to the power of both sides of the equation. (This works only when dealing with equations in which there is no sum or difference inside the log function.)

